00:00:34.766 --> 00:00:36.136
Hal: Ok, thanks.

00:00:36.136 --> 00:00:38.420
Okay hi.

00:00:38.420 --> 00:00:41.626
Hari asked me to talk about
complex systems, which

00:00:41.626 --> 00:00:46.660
is kind of what you've
been studying all semester.

00:00:46.660 --> 00:00:49.856
Today I want to
give you of a hint

00:00:49.856 --> 00:00:52.150
of another kind of complexity.

00:00:52.150 --> 00:00:56.260
You have been doing the
technical infrastructure

00:00:56.260 --> 00:01:02.100
for essentially what has
become the information age.

00:01:02.100 --> 00:01:05.540
But the information age...

00:01:05.540 --> 00:01:07.340
You gotta turn off the mic.

00:01:07.340 --> 00:01:14.580
But the information age has
just changed the world immensely

00:01:14.580 --> 00:01:17.330
over the last 20 years
and has run smack

00:01:17.330 --> 00:01:19.920
into another kind of complexity.

00:01:19.920 --> 00:01:25.180
And that's the complexity of
how the stuff that we have all

00:01:25.190 --> 00:01:32.140
built as computer scientists
and engineers has created

00:01:32.150 --> 00:01:34.700
these enormous stressors
in the way people

00:01:34.700 --> 00:01:38.280
think about the legal structures
and the regulatory structures,

00:01:38.280 --> 00:01:40.479
the way people deal
with the world.

00:01:40.479 --> 00:01:45.560
And why would you guys know, from
being a source of it,

00:01:45.560 --> 00:01:47.700
know that it's a problem?

00:01:47.700 --> 00:01:50.220
But in order to make use of that...

00:01:50.220 --> 00:01:52.600
you have to understand that
suddenly you're dealing with

00:01:52.600 --> 00:01:53.140
the real world.

00:01:53.140 --> 00:01:56.560
It's not just problem sets
or it's not just little

00:01:56.560 --> 00:02:01.540
