or how authorization works.

00:02:01.540 --> 00:02:04.714
It is real impact
on people's lives.

00:02:04.714 --> 00:02:06.630
And you run into people
who think differently.

00:02:06.630 --> 00:02:08.003
And, in particular,
you are going

00:02:08.003 --> 00:02:12.120
to have to learn to think
about how lawmakers and the law

00:02:12.120 --> 00:02:15.840
and lots of other
institutions deal with this.

00:02:15.840 --> 00:02:18.290
This lecture, if
you like, is partly

00:02:18.290 --> 00:02:22.880
a bit of an advertisement
for 6.805 which, of course,

00:02:22.880 --> 00:02:26.060
I teach in the fall.

00:02:26.060 --> 00:02:33.390
And what 6.805 really is
about is empowering you.

00:02:33.390 --> 00:02:37.760
What you have to understand
is by having taken

00:02:37.760 --> 00:02:40.790
the courses you taken
like 6.033, you now

00:02:40.790 --> 00:02:45.737
know more about the
information architecture

00:02:45.740 --> 00:02:46.820
that makes the world work.

00:02:46.820 --> 00:02:52.329
And all but the most minuscule
part of humanity.

00:02:52.329 --> 00:02:56.079
And that can be a
way to have impact,

00:02:56.079 --> 00:02:58.920
but only if you understand
how that impacts

00:02:58.930 --> 00:03:00.550
the regulatory structure.

00:03:00.550 --> 00:03:06.310
Just to give you a tiny example,
about two weeks ago the MBTA

00:03:06.310 --> 00:03:11.460
put out for comments, their
new privacy policy which

00:03:11.460 --> 00:03:14.950
was stimulated by the fact
that the MBTA is planning

00:03:14.950 --> 00:03:19.860
on instituting a new fare
system that uses RFID tokens.

00:03:19.860 --> 00:03:22.250
And one of the things
that went into that policy

00:03:22.250 --> 00:03:28.240
is a whole bunch of criticism by
a student project team in 6.805

00:03:28.240 --> 00:03:32.930
last fall who worked with
the state senator who

00:03:32.930 --> 00:03:35.730
was getting on the MBTA's
case about not having

00:03:35.730 --> 00:03:38.000
adequate privacy regulations.

00:03:38.000 --> 00:03:39.740
So this bunch of MIT
students essentially

00:03:39.740 --> 00:03:42.329
wrote the privacy
regulations that

00:03:42.329 --> 00:03:44.451
are now being sent
out to the public

00:03:44.451 --> 00:03:45.700
in the State of Massachusetts.

00:03:45.700 --> 00:03:49.300
That's a tiny example
of the kind of thing

00:03:49.300 --> 00:03:53.241
that you are now prepared to
do better than almost anybody

00:03:53.241 --> 00:03:53.990
else in the world.

00:03:56.640 --> 00:03:58.579
What I am going to
talk about today

00:03:58.579 --> 00:04:04.780
is how these new architectures,
the ones you've been studying,

00:04:04.780 --> 00:04:06.992
as you've already
seen, what happens

00:04:06.992 --> 00:04:08.700
when you have a big
complex architecture,

00:04:08.700 --> 00:04:10.741
you have to think about
interactions of protocols

00:04:10.741 --> 00:04:13.950
and their standards and
their enormous unintended

00:04:13.950 --> 00:04:16.337
consequences of things
fitting together.

00:04:16.337 --> 00:04:18.670
That's what you've been doing,
for lots of the semester,

00:04:18.670 --> 00:04:19.988
is using understanding that.

00:04:19.988 --> 00:04:21.529
But today I want to
talk a little bit

00:04:21.529 --> 00:04:26.000
about how the same thing happens
with the legal architecture.

00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:28.020
There are protocols,
there are standards

00:04:28.020 --> 00:04:32.470
and there are enormous,
enormous unintended consequences

00:04:32.470 --> 00:04:39.740
of people working on different
parts of a complex system.

00:04:39.740 --> 00:04:42.420
Well, I am not going to
talk about privacy today.

00:04:42.420 --> 00:04:45.010
That is a thing that
the fall course does.

00:04:45.010 --> 00:04:51.650
Today I want to talk about
regulating speech, you know,

00:04:51.650 --> 00:04:54.670
speech, images, sounds,
the way that society

00:04:54.670 --> 00:04:58.150
thinks about that
and sort of the mess

00:04:58.150 --> 00:05:01.360
that the Internet has
created around that.

00:05:01.360 --> 00:05:04.690
And so we can take like
the simplest picture.

00:05:04.690 --> 00:05:08.240
There is the Internet and
there is a source some place

00:05:08.240 --> 00:05:10.220
and there is a
destination some place

00:05:10.220 --> 00:05:12.740
and then there is this cloud
that is the Internet that they

00:05:12.740 --> 00:05:14.170
are communicating with.

00:05:14.170 --> 00:05:16.620
And that is the stupidest
simplest picture.

00:05:16.620 --> 00:05:19.170
You guys know infinitely
more about this picture.

00:05:19.170 --> 00:05:23.330
Just to unpeel the very
first level of that.

00:05:23.330 --> 00:05:27.100
You know that both the source
and destination are probably

00:05:27.100 --> 00:05:30.577
connected to the Net using
an Internet service provider.

00:05:30.577 --> 00:05:32.159
And then, of course,
inside that cloud

00:05:32.159 --> 00:05:34.050
that is all sorts of stuff.

00:05:34.050 --> 00:05:37.840
There are Cisco switched
and hubs and phone companies

00:05:37.840 --> 00:05:39.340
and all sorts of
things translating.

00:05:39.340 --> 00:05:42.230
You can fill out the complexity
of that picture right now,

00:05:42.230 --> 00:05:44.540
but let's stay even
at the simple one.

00:05:44.540 --> 00:05:48.140
Suppose something
is happening there

00:05:48.140 --> 00:05:53.360
that somebody doesn't like.

00:05:53.360 --> 00:05:59.909
Somebody is downloading
copyrighted music or something

00:05:59.909 --> 00:06:01.940
and the recording
industry hates that.

00:06:01.940 --> 00:06:07.660
Somebody is sending threatening
letters to somebody else.

00:06:07.660 --> 00:06:10.660
Somebody is doing
gambling at a place where

00:06:10.660 --> 00:06:11.910
you're not supposed to gamble.

00:06:11.910 --> 00:06:15.050
Something that
somebody doesn't like.

00:06:15.050 --> 00:06:18.990
And let's think
about we, society,

00:06:18.990 --> 00:06:23.420
would like to figure out how you
can stop that or make it happen

00:06:23.420 --> 00:06:25.840
less by imposing regulation.

00:06:28.360 --> 00:06:32.890
And the question is in
any of these transactions

00:06:32.890 --> 00:06:36.610
there are all sorts of places
that you can impose regulation.

00:06:36.610 --> 00:06:39.630
You can go to the source
and you can say, hey,

00:06:39.630 --> 00:06:44.750
stop sending that pornography.

00:06:44.750 --> 00:06:46.600
You could go to the
destination and you

00:06:46.600 --> 00:06:51.890
would say, hey, stop pulling
down that copyrighted music.

00:06:51.890 --> 00:06:53.340
You could go to the ISPs.

00:06:53.340 --> 00:06:58.790
I am sure nobody here has
ever downloaded copyrighted

00:06:58.790 --> 00:07:00.160
music over the Internet.

00:07:00.170 --> 00:07:03.560
But you can imagine the RIAA
going to MIT and saying, hey,

00:07:03.560 --> 00:07:06.700
MIT, you are the ISP
for this connection,

00:07:06.700 --> 00:07:09.330
you put a stop to it.

00:07:09.330 --> 00:07:14.570
You can even imagine
somebody going to the cloud.

00:07:14.570 --> 00:07:17.040
You can imagine congress
passing a regulation,

00:07:17.040 --> 00:07:20.780
or maybe you can imagine it, but
unfortunately a lot of congress

00:07:20.780 --> 00:07:24.200
can imagine passing a regulation
that says something like, hey,

00:07:24.200 --> 00:07:31.090
let's change those Cisco routers
so that they won't pass along

00:07:31.090 --> 00:07:34.520
copyrighted information
without permission.

00:07:34.520 --> 00:07:35.909
And everybody
here, hopefully you

00:07:35.909 --> 00:07:37.461
are shrinking in
horror because you

00:07:37.461 --> 00:07:39.460
know about things like
the end-to-end principle,

00:07:39.460 --> 00:07:41.760
and you say oh, my
God, that violates

00:07:41.760 --> 00:07:43.997
the end-to-to principle in
a horrible, horrible way.

00:07:43.997 --> 00:07:45.580
But you don't think
people in congress

00:07:45.580 --> 00:07:48.740
know about the
end-to-end principle.

00:07:48.740 --> 00:07:51.650
They need people like you
guys to explain it to them.

00:07:51.650 --> 00:07:55.500
That is the kind of thing that
you can become empowered to do.

00:07:59.590 --> 00:08:04.000
Within that context, let's
think about controlling

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:06.590
what people can say and how
people can express themselves

00:08:06.590 --> 00:08:09.674
in words or music or
images or whatever.

00:08:09.674 --> 00:08:11.090
Somebody comes
down and says, hey,

00:08:11.090 --> 00:08:15.850
stop doing that, you really
shouldn't post that thing,

00:08:15.850 --> 00:08:19.230
it is bugging somebody to hell.

00:08:19.230 --> 00:08:25.797
And you say oh, no, because
I've got freedom of speech.

00:08:25.797 --> 00:08:27.130
Let's look at freedom of speech.

00:08:27.130 --> 00:08:30.330
Where does freedom of speech
come from in this country?

00:08:30.330 --> 00:08:31.690
The First Amendment.

00:08:31.690 --> 00:08:34.659
This country has
the First Amendment.

00:08:34.659 --> 00:08:42.390
Congress shall make no law
respecting the establishment

00:08:42.390 --> 00:08:45.430
of religion, or abridging the
freedom of speech, dot, dot,

00:08:45.430 --> 00:08:46.710
dot, dot, dot.

00:08:46.710 --> 00:08:48.710
So let's spend a little
bit thinking about that.

00:08:51.220 --> 00:08:57.870
What does it mean when it says
congress shall make no law?

00:08:57.870 --> 00:09:00.765
Who is Congress?

00:09:00.765 --> 00:09:01.640
Congress is congress.

00:09:04.280 --> 00:09:06.310
Who else is restricted
by the First Amendment?

00:09:06.310 --> 00:09:08.010
Is the State of
Massachusetts congress?

00:09:08.010 --> 00:09:09.960
When the State of
Massachusetts passes

00:09:09.960 --> 00:09:15.360
a law that says you may
not post this certain kind

00:09:15.360 --> 00:09:17.950
of information, you may not
post harassing information

00:09:17.950 --> 00:09:25.189
on the Internet, well,
let me be more precise,

00:09:25.189 --> 00:09:27.230
could they do it within
the confines of the First

00:09:27.230 --> 00:09:27.730
Amendment?

00:09:32.870 --> 00:09:34.359
We know that
congress is congress.

00:09:34.359 --> 00:09:35.900
How about the State
of Massachusetts,

00:09:35.900 --> 00:09:38.050
are they congress?

00:09:38.050 --> 00:09:42.970
It actually turns out the
State of Massachusetts

00:09:42.970 --> 00:09:46.090
is congress for the
First Amendment.

00:09:46.090 --> 00:09:54.210
The Constitution is
the law of the land.

00:09:54.210 --> 00:09:55.840
The Constitution
says what it says.

00:09:55.840 --> 00:09:57.490
It says congress cannot do it.

00:09:57.490 --> 00:10:01.882
And the Supreme Court
has interpreted congress

00:10:01.882 --> 00:10:03.340
to mean the State
of Massachusetts.

00:10:03.340 --> 00:10:06.830
How about if the City of
Cambridge passes a law that

00:10:06.830 --> 00:10:11.470
says you cannot send
these kinds of things?

00:10:14.259 --> 00:10:16.300
Well, it turns out the
City of Cambridge is, too.

00:10:16.300 --> 00:10:19.490
It turns out the First Amendment
covers most governmental things

00:10:19.490 --> 00:10:20.270
in the US.

00:10:20.270 --> 00:10:20.950
How about MIT?

00:10:25.930 --> 00:10:29.440
Could MIT, for example,
have a rule that says that?

00:10:37.470 --> 00:10:40.930
Can there be an MIT
regulation that says that?

00:10:40.930 --> 00:10:43.450
How many people
think there could be?

00:10:43.450 --> 00:10:47.750
And, by could, I mean without
violating the Constitution.

00:10:47.750 --> 00:10:51.360
How many people think
MIT could do that?

00:10:51.360 --> 00:10:53.179
How many people
think MIT cannot?

00:10:53.179 --> 00:10:55.720
You go and take them to court
and say it is unconstitutional.

00:11:00.280 --> 00:11:04.810
How about UMass Boston?

00:11:04.810 --> 00:11:06.710
Could UMass Boston
have a regulation

00:11:06.710 --> 00:11:12.570
like that without violating
the First Amendment?

00:11:12.570 --> 00:11:13.320
What do you think?

00:11:13.320 --> 00:11:14.611
How many people think it could?

00:11:17.370 --> 00:11:20.480
How many people
think it couldn't?

00:11:20.480 --> 00:11:22.950
How many people have no idea?

00:11:22.950 --> 00:11:25.190
Well, sort of have no
idea is the right answer.

00:11:25.190 --> 00:11:28.230
But it kind of turns out that
this language actually comes

00:11:28.230 --> 00:11:32.640
exactly from a policy at
the University of Michigan

00:11:32.640 --> 00:11:36.900
ten years ago which was
struck down by the court.

00:11:41.290 --> 00:11:46.860
That was, whatever we call
these things, harassment policy

00:11:46.860 --> 00:11:47.509
or something.

00:11:47.509 --> 00:11:49.300
That was actually struck
down by the court.

00:11:49.300 --> 00:11:51.799
And what the judge said was,
look, this might be a good idea

00:11:51.799 --> 00:11:53.720
and we might like it,
but in this country

00:11:53.720 --> 00:11:58.270
government institutions
like by extension

00:11:58.270 --> 00:12:00.860
of the State of Michigan and
the University of Michigan

00:12:00.860 --> 00:12:02.485
are constrained by
the First Amendment.

00:12:06.610 --> 00:12:07.854
MIT is not.

00:12:07.854 --> 00:12:09.770
We can argue whether or
not it is a good idea,

00:12:09.770 --> 00:12:13.840
but it is not unconstitutional
for MIT to do that.

00:12:13.840 --> 00:12:18.100
Now, you might ask
do you guys have

00:12:18.100 --> 00:12:21.390
less solid guarantees
of freedom of speech

00:12:21.390 --> 00:12:24.181
than students at UMass Boston?

00:12:24.181 --> 00:12:25.055
Well, yeah, probably.

00:12:29.840 --> 00:12:32.000
There are lots of
things that congress,

00:12:32.000 --> 00:12:35.360
and by the extension of
congress, cannot prohibit.

00:12:37.480 --> 00:12:40.180
But what are some things
that congress can prohibit?

00:12:40.180 --> 00:12:42.980
What are some kinds of speech
or images or things that you

00:12:42.980 --> 00:12:46.380
actually can have laws against?

00:12:48.060 --> 00:12:49.040
What do you think?

00:12:49.040 --> 00:12:51.160
Are there any limits
to this at all?

00:12:51.160 --> 00:12:51.660
What do you think?

00:12:54.820 --> 00:12:57.800
Is there any kind of thing
that you have limits?

00:12:57.800 --> 00:13:00.020
Student: Yelling fire in a public theater.

00:13:02.800 --> 00:13:05.420
Student: Something that is
truly very dangerous.

00:13:05.440 --> 00:13:06.660
This is about speech.

00:13:06.660 --> 00:13:07.680
This is not about actions.

00:13:07.680 --> 00:13:11.660
Are there kinds of speech
or images of things?

00:13:11.670 --> 00:13:12.820
Child pornography.

00:13:12.820 --> 00:13:16.770
We cannot actually possess child
pornography in this country.

00:13:16.770 --> 00:13:19.460
We will get back to
that in a second.

00:13:19.460 --> 00:13:24.180
Anything that can be defined
as interstate commerce?

00:13:24.180 --> 00:13:27.911
No, that just means you
cannot reregulate it.

00:13:27.911 --> 00:13:30.160
I am asking what are some
examples of stuff you cannot

00:13:30.160 --> 00:13:32.260
post on the Internet.

00:13:32.260 --> 00:13:35.860
Libel or slander.

00:13:35.860 --> 00:13:41.310
There is a whole bit of
that copyright infringement

00:13:41.310 --> 00:13:42.080
we talk about.

00:13:42.080 --> 00:13:44.050
How about pornography?

00:13:44.050 --> 00:13:50.030
You get in trouble for posting
pornography on the Internet.

00:13:50.030 --> 00:13:53.540
Can that be prohibited
under state law?

00:13:53.540 --> 00:13:56.960
It turns out it depends what
you mean by pornography.

00:13:56.960 --> 00:13:58.370
In fact, if we
sort of elevate up

00:13:58.370 --> 00:14:00.650
from pornography to
what is normally called,

00:14:00.650 --> 00:14:05.320
you know, pornography
is bad, but really bad.

00:14:05.320 --> 00:14:10.820
The word for really bad
in US law is obscenity.

00:14:10.820 --> 00:14:13.962
And it turns out, well,
let's see if you know.

00:14:13.962 --> 00:14:16.170
Do you think there is a
legal definition of obscenity

00:14:16.170 --> 00:14:20.860
or is it like hey, it
is really bad stuff?

00:14:20.860 --> 00:14:23.840
How many think there is a
formal legal definition when

00:14:23.840 --> 00:14:27.340
the court looks at something
and says it is obscene?

00:14:27.340 --> 00:14:32.076
And how many think it is
like really bad stuff?

00:14:32.076 --> 00:14:33.200
The first people are right.

00:14:33.200 --> 00:14:34.810
There actually is,
in this country,

00:14:34.810 --> 00:14:38.480
a legal definition of obscenity
which was established in a case

00:14:38.480 --> 00:14:39.280
called Miller v.

00:14:39.280 --> 00:14:41.030
California in the `70s.

00:14:41.030 --> 00:14:44.185
And it says this is the
definition of obscenity

00:14:44.185 --> 00:14:45.060
according to the law.

00:14:45.060 --> 00:14:47.220
It is called the Miller Test.

00:14:47.220 --> 00:14:52.240
It says something is
obscene if it satisfied all

00:14:52.240 --> 00:14:54.060
of the following three things.

00:14:54.060 --> 00:14:56.060
A three have to be true.

00:14:56.060 --> 00:14:59.440
The first one is that it
depicts sexual activity

00:14:59.440 --> 00:15:02.690
in a patently offensive way.

00:15:02.690 --> 00:15:04.540
So like it is not
an anatomy book.

00:15:07.180 --> 00:15:08.792
That is sort about
what the stuff is.

00:15:08.792 --> 00:15:10.500
The second one is how
people react to it.

00:15:10.500 --> 00:15:12.630
It is a very interesting test.

00:15:12.630 --> 00:15:25.510
It says would the average person
applying contemporary community

00:15:25.510 --> 00:15:30.760
standards find that that appeals
to the prurient interest?

