which I won't go into here,

00:36:47.600 --> 00:36:52.560
but the net result was
the Supreme Court decided

00:36:52.560 --> 00:36:56.780
that the Display Provision of
the Communications Decency Act

00:36:56.780 --> 00:36:58.840
was unconstitutional.

00:37:03.740 --> 00:37:06.040
Right, and they said...

00:37:06.040 --> 00:37:11.060
they said why? The community
standards are too broad.

00:37:11.060 --> 00:37:15.630
If you apply that it means
the standard of the most

00:37:15.630 --> 00:37:18.490
restrictive community
will start replying

00:37:18.490 --> 00:37:19.960
across the whole country.

00:37:19.960 --> 00:37:24.430
And it turns out
the government can

00:37:24.430 --> 00:37:27.850
pass laws to protect
kids access to stuff,

00:37:27.850 --> 00:37:31.970
but they say in this case, by
this desire to protect kids,

00:37:31.970 --> 00:37:34.050
you are restricting
adults from what

00:37:34.050 --> 00:37:36.330
they should be able to get.

00:37:36.330 --> 00:37:39.010
Anyway, a long, very, very
important First Amendment

00:37:39.010 --> 00:37:45.220
decision, Reno v. ACLU.

00:37:45.220 --> 00:37:49.780
The Supreme Court ruling came
down and everybody was happy,

00:37:49.780 --> 00:37:51.890
civil liberty groups,
everybody jumped up and down

00:37:51.890 --> 00:37:57.111
and said the Internet is a zone
of free speech, which brings us

00:37:57.111 --> 00:37:57.611
